{"parse":{"title":"Criminal appeal","pageid":40341533,"revid":740415241,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div role=\"note\" class=\"hatnote navigation-not-searchable\">This article is about the obsolete legal procedure. For the process of reviewing a decision already made by a court, see <a href=\"/wiki/Appeal\" title=\"Appeal\">Appeal</a> or <a href=\"/wiki/Appellate_court\" title=\"Appellate court\">Appellate court</a></div>\n<p>A <b>criminal appeal</b> was a procedure in <a href=\"/wiki/English_law\" title=\"English law\">English law</a> to bring about the <a href=\"/wiki/Prosecution\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Prosecution\">prosecution</a> of an individual accused of some crime. A private individual (the \"appellor\") would accuse another (the \"appellee\") of a crime, without the need for proceedings to be brought by the <a href=\"/wiki/The_Crown\" title=\"The Crown\">crown</a>. It possibly descended from the system of <a href=\"/wiki/Weregild\" title=\"Weregild\">weregild</a>.\n</p><p>Appeals were among the legal proceedings for which <a href=\"/wiki/Trial_by_combat\" title=\"Trial by combat\">trial by combat</a> was available.\n</p><p>An appeal could be used to accuse a <a href=\"/wiki/British_subject\" title=\"British subject\">subject</a> of <a href=\"/wiki/High_treason\" title=\"High treason\">high treason</a>. It could also be used by someone when either they or a close relation had been the victim of a crime, such as <a href=\"/wiki/Murder\" title=\"Murder\">murder</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Rape\" title=\"Rape\">rape</a> or <a href=\"/wiki/Arson\" title=\"Arson\">arson</a>.\n</p><p>An acquittal following an appeal prevented any further prosecution for the same offence (the doctrine of <a href=\"/wiki/Double_jeopardy\" title=\"Double jeopardy\">double jeopardy</a>), just as if the proceedings had been brought by the crown (by <a href=\"/wiki/Indictment\" title=\"Indictment\">indictment</a>). The person bringing the appeal would be punished.\n</p><p>Unlike crown prosecutions, if a person was convicted, the crown did not have the option of a <a href=\"/wiki/Pardon\" title=\"Pardon\">pardon</a>.\n</p><p>Appeals were abolished in <a href=\"/wiki/England_and_Wales\" title=\"England and Wales\">England</a> following the 1817 case of <a href=\"/wiki/Ashford_v_Thornton\" title=\"Ashford v Thornton\">Ashford v Thornton</a> where an appeal was withdrawn following the defendant requesting a trial by battle.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Criminal_appeal&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li>William Blackstone, <i>Commentaries on the Laws of England</i>, Book 4, Chapter XXII \"Of the several modes of prosecution\", Section IV</li></ul>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks stub\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"background:transparent\"><tbody><tr><td><a href=\"/wiki/File:Scale_of_justice_2.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Stub icon\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0e/Scale_of_justice_2.svg/22px-Scale_of_justice_2.svg.png\" width=\"22\" height=\"22\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0e/Scale_of_justice_2.svg/33px-Scale_of_justice_2.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0e/Scale_of_justice_2.svg/44px-Scale_of_justice_2.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"204\" data-file-height=\"208\" /></a></td><td><i>This <a href=\"/wiki/Law\" title=\"Law\">law</a>-related article is a <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Stub\" title=\"Wikipedia:Stub\">stub</a>. You can help Wikipedia by <a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Criminal_appeal&amp;action=edit\">expanding it</a>.</i><div class=\"plainlinks hlist navbar mini\" style=\"position: absolute; right: 15px; display: none;\"><ul><li class=\"n